			<h1><span class="less"><a href="index.html">SLE 2022</a> paper:</span><br><i>A Multi-target, Multi-paradigm DSL Compiler for Algorithmic Graph Processing</i></h1>
			<h2><a href="../profile/HoudaBoukham.html">Houda Boukham</a>, <a href="../profile/GuidoWachsmuth.html">Guido Wachsmuth</a>, <a href="../profile/MartijnDwars.html">Martijn Dwars</a>, <a href="../profile/DalilaChiadmi.html">Dalila Chiadmi</a></h2>
<ul><li>DOI: <a href="https://doi.org/10.1145/3567512.3567513">10.1145/3567512.3567513</a></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t4c.html"><span class="tagM">T4C: Vertical Transformation</span></a><ul><li> The core contribution is a compiler pipeline that generates code for multiple targets/paradigms from a DSL.
</li></ul></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t3c.html"><span class="tagL">T3C: DSLs</span></a><ul><li> It is centered on a domain-specific language for algorithmic graph processing.
</li></ul></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t2d.html"><span class="tagL">T2D: Deployment</span></a><ul><li> Multi-target compilation directly supports portability across execution platforms.
</li></ul></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t5f.html"><span class="tagL">T5F: Performance</span></a><ul><li> Graph-processing compilation choices are motivated by efficiency of the generated programs.
</li></ul></li></ul>
